sentences: Tais Teng (born 1952 in The Hague) is the pen name of a Dutch writer of fantasy fiction, hardboiled detective, children's books and science fiction.

In the Netherlands Tais Teng is best known as a member of the Griezelgenootschap, a group of Dutch horror writers who published a yearbook of horror stories and gave performances and signing sessions for interested fans from 1994 to 2003.
In 2019 wrote the novel Phaedra: Alastor 824, an authorised sequel to the Alastor Cluster novels of the grandmaster himself.

Tais Teng began first selling his art work in 1981, the same year he wrote his first children's book and published a sf collection for adults.
Other pen names he used are Eban Hourst and Ben Bergen.

In the Netherlands Tais Teng is best known as a member of the Griezelgenootschap, a group of Dutch horror writers who published a yearbook of horror stories and gave performances and signing sessions for interested fans from 1994 to 2003.
Tais Teng wrote the three-novel-series Duisterlingen (Darklings) with Eddy C. Bertin and Bies van Ede about three children with special powers who can travel into the nightmarish dreamland Yldorgei.
Monus, de Man van de Maan (Monus, the Man from the Moon) by A.D. Hildebrandt was an extremely popular audioplay which was aired every week.

He used oils and acrylic paint and while oil paint looked better, it also took a fortnight to dry, which can be a problem when a publisher is waiting for the cover.

The technique was perfect to paint the surrealistic Salvador Dalí inspired twilight skies so often used in science fiction, but the painting was easily spoiled when the flow of paint started spattering.
Nowadays Tais Teng makes use of computer generated Fractals and kaleidoscopic madalas to construct his landscapes.
For smaller pieces he also uses springstone, a quite hard material often used in African art.

Two of the most extreme samples: "Why we are standing on a broken wall, clutching swords too rusty to take an edge" and "A perfect day with the dead men shrieking and the sky filled with northern light.
